piece of advice as part of preconception counselling?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Amniocentesis will be required in the second trimester because of the increased risk of fetal abnormalities associated with anticonvulsant drugs","Commence 5mg folic acid daily preconception and throughout the first trimester","Change carbamazepine to sodium valproate prior to conception","Regular monitoring of antiepileptic drug serum levels is required","Breastfeeding whilst taking carbamazepine is not recommended"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EEpilepsy is a common condition and most women with epilepsy will need to continue antiepileptic drugs (AEDs) during pregnancy. Lowest dose monotherapy with either levetiracetam, carbamazepine, or lamotrigine is the preferred primary treatment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESupplementation with \u003Cstrong\u003E5mg folic acid per day\u003C/strong\u003E is recommended for all women with epilepsy, starting 3 months prior to conception and throughout the first trimester. Women on antiepileptic drugs are recommended to take a higher dose of folic acid (5mg instead of 0.5mg) because these medications can interfere with folate metabolism, increasing the risk of neural tube defects in the developing fetus.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELevetiracetam and lamotrigine have a low risk profile but doses may need to be increased in pregnancy. Carbamazepine monotherapy at low doses have lower risk of major congenital malformations compared to \u003Cstrong\u003Esodium valproate \u003C/strong\u003Eand therefore switching antiepileptics in a stable patient is not recommended. The most common congenital malformations include neural tube defects, congenital heart disorders, urinary tract and skeletal abnormalities, and cleft palate.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAmniocentesis\u003C/strong\u003E for the detection of an AED related malformation is not necessary as abnormalities are often detected on early ultrasound at 12-16 weeks gestation or at the detailed morphology scan at 18-22 weeks.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESeizure frequency does not normally increase during pregnancy with 67% of women remaining seizure free. There is no evidence that \u003Cstrong\u003Emonitoring of serum anti-epileptic drug levels\u003C/strong\u003E improves seizure control.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBreastfeeding\u003C/strong\u003E whilst taking carbamazepine is considered safe as only very small quantities are excreted in the breast milk. The benefits of breastfeeding generally outweigh any theoretical risks, and women should be encouraged to breastfeed if they wish to do so.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Folic acid supplements are advised for patients taking carbamazepine and planning pregnancy."],"references":["Thangaratinam S, Marlin N, Newton S, Weckesser A, Bagary M, Greenhill L, Rikunenko R, D\u0027Amico M, Rogozi\u0144ska E, Kelso A, Hard K, Coleman J, Moss N, Roberts T, Middleton L, Dodds J, Pullen A, Eldridge S, Pirie A, Denny E, McCorry D, Khan KS. AntiEpileptic drug Monitoring in PREgnancy (EMPiRE): a double-blind randomised trial on effectiveness and acceptability of monitoring strategies. Health Technol Assess. 2018 May;22(23):1-152. doi: 10.3310/hta22230. PMID: 29737274; PMCID: PMC5960819.","RCOG Green-top Guideline No. 6. June 2016. Epilepsy in Pregnancy. Royal College of Obstetricians and Gynaecologists. https://www.rcog.org.uk/globalassets/documents/guidelines/green-top-guidelines/gtg68_epilepsy.pdf. Accessed December 18, 2020.","Gandelman-Marton R, Neufeld M. [Epilepsy in pregnancy]. Harefuah. 2013 Aug;152(8):473-6, 498. Hebrew. PMID: 24167933."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98468"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2318"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98468","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.c